I was able to fix this last night.  The "do the business" was sending a list of resources and object values from the ResultSet to a ThreadPoolExecutor to process over 64 cores.  Whereas, the individual threads kept mostly to themselves,  each was adding the results back to the original Model as follows:
```
m.enterCriticalSection(Lock.WRITE);
m.add(z);
m.leaveCriticalSection();
```
The code work for thousands of large graphs, but for one, kept throwing the same above error.  I was able to fix the issue by buffering up all of the threads and then calling engine.prestartAllCoreThreads() after the
```
rs.forEachRemaining(qs->{
    do the business *
    });
```
loop was done.  ResultSet rs = qe.execSelect().materialise(); looks like it would have solved the issue too so I will have to give it a try.  Thanks!
